<div class = "home_text" >
  <!-- <div class="closeIt">CLOSE</div> -->	
  <h1>	What is the 'second road'?</h1>
  <div class="col450">
	<p>The Western world, from Aristotle onwards, has sought truth and direction along two different paths:</p> 
	<ul>
	  <li>a first road represented by the principles of logic, the engine room of analysis and analytic inquiry</li>
	  <li>a second road constituted by the principles of rhetoric - persuasive argument, intent, invention and socialisation.</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Aristotle’s opinion was that the first road is most suitable for answering questions of science and nature, the second for managing human nature and civic affairs.</p> 	
	<p>Both roads are powerful. Both yield insights. Both are necessary.</p> 
	<p>Our business world today, however, is not what it was a century, or even a decade ago. Interconnectedness, velocity, volatile change and the critical importance of people make it impossible to simply ‘make a plan and stick to it’. Logic and analysis alone are not enough to prepare an organisation for a future in a shifting, global environment.</p> 
	<p>Business leaders today need the second road - the path of invention and design - to envision compelling yet flexible strategy, create common purpose and mobilise people into action. They need new skills derived from the arts of design, language and storytelling.</p> 
	<p>Second Road is at the forefront of the ‘second road’ today.</p> 
  </div>	
</div>




